04407nam a22005775i 9780300188325DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001883257 a10.12987/97803001883252doi  a(DE-B1597)486280  a(OCoLC)823931244  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aHIS0360202bisacsh04a277.3/07092aB2231 aBrekus, Catherine A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSarah Osborn's World :bThe Rise of Evangelical Christianity in Early America /cCatherine A. Brekus. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (448 p.) :b23 b-w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Directions in Narrative History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: A MEMOIR, 1743 -- tChapter 1. Never Despair -- tChapter 2. The Name of Christ -- tChapter 3. An Afflicted Low Condition -- tChapter 4. Amazing Grace -- tPart Two: DIARIES AND LETTERS, 1744 –1796 -- tChapter 5. The Lord Gave, and the Lord Hath Taken Away, 1744 -- tChapter 6. No Imaginary Thing, 1753–1755 -- tChapter 7. Pinching Poverty, 1756 –1758 -- tChapter 8. Love Thy Neighbor, 1759–1763 -- tChapter 9. Jordan Overflowing, 1765 –1774 -- tChapter 10. The Latter Days, 1775 –1787 -- tChapter 11. The Open Vision, 1796 -- tEpilogue: A Protestant Saint -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1743, sitting quietly with pen in hand, Sarah Osborn pondered how to tell the story of her life, how to make sense of both her spiritual awakening and the sudden destitution of her family. Remarkably, the memoir she created that year survives today, as do more than two thousand additional pages she composed over the following three decades. Sarah Osborn's World is the first book to mine this remarkable woman’s prolific personal and spiritual record. Catherine Brekus recovers the largely forgotten story of Sarah Osborn's life as one of the most charismatic female religious leaders of her time, while also connecting her captivating story to the rising evangelical movement in eighteenth-century America.A schoolteacher in Rhode Island, a wife, and a mother, Sarah Osborn led a remarkable revival in the 1760s that brought hundreds of people, including many slaves, to her house each week. Her extensive written record-encompassing issues ranging from the desire to be "born again" to a suspicion of capitalism-provides a unique vantage point from which to view the emergence of evangelicalism. Brekus sets Sarah Osborn's experience in the context of her revivalist era and expands our understanding of the birth of the evangelical movement-a movement that transformed Protestantism in the decades before the American Revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristian biographyzUnited States. 0aChristian womenzRhode IslandvBiography. 0aEvangelical RevivalzUnited Statesy18th century. 0aEvangelistszRhode IslandvBiography. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030018290340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030018832540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300188325423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300188325/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY